Defines M2 theme tokens (CSS vars) inline instead of creating a new selector block

```
// Theme file:
html {
  @include mat.button-theme($theme);
  @include mat.card-theme($theme);
  @include mat.checkbox-theme($theme);
}
```

Before, this would have split each component into its own html block:
```
html {
  // button token CSS variable definitions
}

html {
  // card token CSS variable definitions
}

html {
  // checkbox token CSS variable definitions
}
```

With this change, these will be grouped together:
```
html {
  // button token CSS variable definitions
  // card token CSS variable definitions
  // checkbox token CSS variable definitions
}
```

For some users, this will surface a Sass warning about [mixed-decls](https://sass-lang.com/documentation/breaking-changes/mixed-decls/). This was previously being avoided because the CSS created the variables in subsequent selector blocks, but are now inline.

When using the **cdkObserveContent** directive, I noticed that it reacts to changes in any content within the element it applies to, not just **ng-content**, or is this a coincidence?

If this is intended, I suggest improving the documentation so that this feature does not seem like a coincidence.
https://material.angular.dev/cdk/observers/overview

_The suggested changes to the code could be edited better to convey the information more simply_

Example:
```html
<div class="content-wrapper" (click)="changeText()" (cdkObserveContent)="textChanged()">
  {{ text }}
</div>
```

